<font color="#FF0000">HISTORICAL SOCIETY INTEREST?</font><br>
<tt>Mon Apr  7  1:58:56 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
There is something that everyone is so far missing when talking about the value of this site--we are gathering personal testimony or historical importance which has not, and could not, be gathered in any other war.  The medium was not there! It is only with the advent of the personal computer and the internet that this information is possible.<br><br>
I have, in the last 6 months, become reacquainted with some of my service buddies.  I have found out that Duane Hackney is dead of a heart attack a few years back.  He had a Silver Star (among many, many other medals) for a rescue in North Vietnam.  Randy McComb also has passed away.  He was on the raid into the San Tai POW camp. <br><br>
What I'm saying is that the people who can contribute now will not be here forever.  This is an unprecedented opportunity to gather information; it shouldn't be thrown away.  <br><br>
Is it possible to find funding based upon the historical importance of this dialog?  We don't have this dialog for the Revolutionary War, the War of 1812, the Civil War, the Indian wars, WW1, WWII, or Korea. Perhaps some very important historical information will be lost if this site is not continued. We may never know, but what if the son or daughter of one of these contributers becomes a VIP 20 to 40 years from now? The thoughts expressed here would then be deemed invaluable. But we cannot, here and now, place a value upon it because we do not yet know the historical significance of this information.<br><br>
Can any historical society help to underwright this site?<br>

<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


